Etymology

[edit]

From the Etruscan letter 𐌕 (t, “te”), from the Ancient Greek letter Τ (T, “tau”), derived from the Phoenician letter 𐤕 (t, “taw”), from the Egyptian hieroglyph 𓏴.

Letter

[edit]

T (lower case t)

  1. The twentieth letter of the basic modern Latin alphabet.

See also

  2. tesla (the SI unit of magnetic flux density)

  6. (genetics, IUPAC 1-letter symbol) thymine
    Synonym: Thy

    Synonym: Thr

  12. (chemistry, physics, deprecated) tritium
    Synonyms: H-3, ³H
    Hypernym: H
    Coordinate terms: H-2, ²H, D; H-4, ⁴H, Q
  14. (linguistics) a wildcard for a tone or stress level (the tonicity of a syllable)

  18. tonne
    Alternative form: t

Central Franconian

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]
  • /t/ is from unshifted West Germanic *t (in tr, ft, st, ht and relicts); occasionally from *d, *þ through analogy (e.g. preterite suffix); from *þþ; in most of Moselle Franconian also from *dd.

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /t/

Letter

[edit]

T

  1. A letter in the German-based alphabet of Central Franconian.
  2. A letter in the Dutch-based alphabet of Central Franconian.

Usage notes

[edit]
Doubling of T
  • In the German-based spelling, t is doubled after short vowels except in certain function words and when the letter is followed by another consonant within the word stem.
  • In the Dutch-based spelling, t is doubled after short vowels if the syllable were otherwise open.

Tagalog

[edit]

Etymology

[edit]

Borrowed from Spanish T. Each pronunciation has a different source:

  • Filipino alphabet pronunciation is influenced by English T.
  • Abecedario pronunciation is from Spanish T.
  • Abakada alphabet pronunciation is influenced by Baybayin character ᜆ (ta).

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • (Standard Tagalog)
    • IPA(key): /ˈti/ [ˈt̪ɪ] (letter name, Filipino alphabet)
      • Rhymes: -i
    • IPA(key): /ˈta/ [ˈt̪a] (letter name, Abakada alphabet)
      • Rhymes: -a
    • IPA(key): /ˈte/ [ˈt̪ɛ] (letter name, Abecedario)
      • Rhymes: -e
    • IPA(key): /t/ [t̪] (phoneme)

Letter

[edit]

T (upper case, lower case t)

  1. The twenty-second letter of the Tagalog alphabet (the Filipino alphabet), called ti and written in the Latin script.
  2. The seventeenth letter of the Tagalog alphabet (the Abakada alphabet), called ta and written in the Latin script.
  3. (historical) The twenty-third letter of the Tagalog alphabet (the Abecedario), called te and written in the Latin script.

See also

[edit]

Mutation

[edit]
  • T at the beginning of words mutates to D in a soft mutation, to Nh in a nasal mutation and to Th in an aspirate mutation, for example with the word Tŷ (“house”):
Mutated forms of Tŷ
radical soft nasal aspirate
Tŷ Dŷ Nhŷ Thŷ

Note: Certain mutated forms of some words can never occur in standard Welsh.
